          "body": "After the portrait of the wicked (vv. 9-10), whose hands hold zimmah (wicked schemes) and shachad (bribes), David returns to petition with the great adversative: 'But as for me, I shall walk in my integrity; redeem me, and be gracious to me' (26:11). The combination of 'integrity' and 'redeem' (padah) is the psalm's most theologically precise moment. padah is not the language of moral achievement rewarded; it is the language of ransom, of the payment of a price to free the captive. David does not say 'I have been so upright that You owe me deliverance.' He says: 'I have oriented my life toward You — now ransom me.' The appeal to integrity provides the moral basis for the plea; the appeal to redemption acknowledges that the deliverance itself is an act of divine initiative and grace. Douglas Moo's observation about James 1's blend of faith and works finds its Old Testament parallel here: integrity and dependence on grace are not alternatives but partners in the covenant life. The final word of the petition — 'be gracious to me' (chanan) — is pure gift-language."
